    "text": "The conditions in statement A (separation of empirical claim, explicit flagging of three assumptions) and statement B (same separation and flagging) are structurally identical, so the statements are not contradictory but complementary: A states the positive condition for admissibility, B states the negative consequence of its absence.",
    "topic": "Logical equivalence of conditions"
  },
  {
    "text": "Admissibility is a strictly formal criterion: the proposal qualifies as a lens suggestion if the empirical claim (“recurs”) is operationally separated from the methodological move and the three implicit assumptions are made explicit, irrespective of the proposal’s eventual substantive merit.",
    "topic": "Formal admissibility boundary"
  },
  {
    "text": "The risk of over-extension (B) materializes only when the admissibility conditions are not met; once the empirical claim is separated and the assumptions (recurrence → relevance; structural similarity; defined long-term) are flagged, the risk is neutralized.",
    "topic": "Risk-condition coupling"
  },
  {
    "text": "The three implicit assumptions that must be flagged are: (i) recurrence indicates relevance, not mere selection bias; (ii) the target problem displays relevant structural similarity; (iii) “long‑term” is defined in a falsifiable manner. Flagging them satisfies both A and B.",
    "topic": "Assumption flagging checklist"
  }
]
